metadata.name: Balanced #200
metadata.description:
What does balance look like when viewed through the lens of pure mathematics? This is the question Balanced attempts to answer.

Each output is composed of a unique collection of blocks mathematically stacked to be in perfect balance.

This is my Genesis project. Enjoy!

Interactions:
1 - Reverse your stack vertically and re-balance.
2 - Toggle between square and portrait frame.
3 - Show center of mass. 
4 - Toggle the border.
5 - Toggle the background (color/transparent)
6 - Export image (2048x2048)
7 - Export image (4096x4096)
8 - Export image (8192x8192)

How it was made: https://www.jeffweber.art/balanced

metadata.name: Reconnaissance #283
metadata.description:
An immense quiet accompanies a sense of looming futility while peering down across vast new worlds. What use is there in discovering and documenting these unknown places? Who would care to seek out lifeless lands lost in the cosmos?

Any civilization capable of such reconnaissance might seem above the little hope that barren lands may bring. Unless, of course, there is a hope of answering the most desperate of needs: Finding a New Home.

Were these images captured by humans on Earth, or on Mars, or somewhere even further away in distance and probability? Maybe they’re recon from another planet’s civilization — one that shares our struggle to find true harmony with the world they have.

Inspired by the remarkable satellite imagery in the compendium “This is Mars,” Reconnaissance suggests what may lie outside our habitable lands — and that we risk missing what's already here while being compelled to look further and further for what’s next.


Choose a resolution (1-6) by adding "&scale=4" to the URL in live view.
Created with p5.js

TENDER x Nat Sarkissian
May 2022

metadata.name: Omega Point #110
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: Citadels, At night. #41
metadata.description:
Citadels, at night is a passion project started short after my Space Anomalies collection. It's inspired by the movement of noise fields and the feeling of space and height you feel often when looking at citadels.

Hoping to bring some joy and beauty with this piece.

Made by Wouter Missler with p5js.

metadata.name: Fictional Cityscapes #17
metadata.description:
Some of the most stunning, and beloved, images are large cities, viewed from afar at the right angle, and preferably with some water in front. 

This project comes from my experiments with line art, and is slightly inspired by Hevey's amazing Dencity drop, which is on a different level to most generative art. 

The cities here are based on some fictional tower architecture and some unusual skies.

Press any key to toggle black background.

Fully deterministic but the higher your viewport the more terrain will be drawn, this is preferable to fixed scaling.

metadata.name: Mur #54
metadata.description:
Mur is a series of computational drawings of stacked and falling bricks. The bricks are placed in different configurations of walls, towers, stacks and paths, and are then exposed to gravity. 

The graphics are coded with p5.js and the rigid body simulations with ammo.js. In live mode, press 's' to save a screenshot and 'e' to save a high resolution image. Press 't' to toggle textures. 

Each scene is drawn twice, first brick by brick as they fall or stay in place, then the scene as a whole. Mur is optimized for Chrome, uses WebGL and may not work in all browsers.

metadata.name: 無山不似山 #34
metadata.description:
「見山是山，見山不是山，見山祇是山。」
Seeing mountains, are:
mountains; 
not mountains; 
just mountains.

“Seeing is forgetting the name of the thing one sees.” - I forgot whom this was from. 
But it’s also never something it's not. Your imagination is not mine. Nor mine yours. 

「作畫必此畫定非知畫人」- 蘇軾
「然須知作此畫而竟不是此畫，則尤非畫人矣。其妙處總在旁見側出，吸取題神；不是此畫，恰是此畫。」- 袁枚

Painting is not exactly this, but yet precisely that. This code and that composition, both, all, neither, are mountains, really, are they not?   

無山不似山？
No mountain is not a mountain. 

p5.js may take a good few seconds to paint. 

Press 1 to save png, only for Chrome, not Safari. But if you wish you can try with Safari. It tries very hard to paint layer by layer. Preview images are compressed.

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

metadata.name: WEIRD FISHES 7, 8, 9 and 10 #8
metadata.description:
Final drop of the WEIRD FISHES serie

Weird Fish 7 - The Bulldog Clownfish (35% probability)
Weird Fish 8 - The Unicorn Fish (30% probability)
Weird Fish 9 - The Guppy Fish (20% probability)
Weird Fish 10 - The Pterois Volitans (15% probability)

These are the 7th, 8th, 9th and 10th in a collection of 10 fish
Each drop in this serie have less possible iterations compared to the previous one, making these new fish the most rare!



This token features:
Many different coral reefs in various colours
Fishes in different sizes and colours
Small fish banks in random number and colour
Random bubbles
Random speed
Perline noise plancton in different quantities size and colour
